title: Grateful Dead Live at Cleveland Public Hall on 1979-11-29
lineage: Master Soundboard Cassette > Cassette > DAT> Cassette > DAT > CDR
description: Alabama Getaway-> Promised Land, They Love Each Other, Mama Tried-> Mexicali Blues, Althea, Easy To Love You, Minglewood Blues, Brown Eyed Women-> Looks Like Rain-> Don't Ease Me In Shakedown Street-> Samson & Delilah, High Time, Estimated Prophet-> Eyes Of The World-> Drums-> Not Fade Away-> Black Peter-> Around & Around-> Johnny B. Goode, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text: Charlie Chan? Solid show and recording, with Jerry adding a special twist to the US Blues encore.
Very nice sounding SBD Very nice sounding SBD, and if you love fall '79 as I do, you should enjoy this show.
Solid show other then the NFA being cut, this is a solid show, both musically and vocally.  Garcia shines throughout........Great list too...nothing like a second set high time.  Good show.

Great sound This is a very fine soundboard , super mix , every instrument defined and crisp. The playing is tight and enthusiastic. Kick ass overall.

I like it.
alrighty this is a pretty good show! Love eyes. Fall 79 is awesome. Awesome set 2!

Mega-Spacey Eyes Good fall 79' the shakedown is really tight, one of the nicer jamming versions. The second set is pretty  nice, with a spectacular Eyes. This really takes you places and has some great brent-and jerry work going on around the 18 minute mark...

grab this one, fall 79 is tasty
3 card monte This was part of a Buffalo,Cleveland,Stanley in Pittsburgh run. I had been laid up after 78 Red Rocks show and these where my first shows back.Great Fun!God those days where a gas.

What a show! One highlight after another in this show. LLR & Eyes super-amazing. Crisp playing, energetic voices, great sound. My only regret is that I never attended a show in this incredible venue. By the time I move to CLE they were already playing in the Coliseum, one of the worst places to see a show (IMHO). Cleveland Public Hall/Auditorium is still standing, the Coliseum is long gone, TG.

P.T. Barnum.... And the Shah of Iran(?)

Turns out this show was a few weeks after the Iranians took over the US embassy in Tehran.

So it was a timely lyric change.
